# AEGIS Pro â€” Backend Setup Guide

The AEGIS Pro app (`aegis-pro.html`) fully implements everything a browser can do on its own: streaming chat, multimodal upload, live web search with citations, focus modes, an artifacts panel, personas, local chat history, and voice mode.

Four features are UI placeholders in that file because they require real, secret-holding infrastructure that can't live in a static frontend. This guide is the "real" version of each.

---

## 1. Real user accounts + database (Supabase)

Supabase is the fastest path: Postgres + Auth + Row Level Security in one project.

**Setup:**
1. Create a project at supabase.com.
2. In the SQL editor, create your chat history table:

```sql
create table chat_sessions (
  id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id uuid references auth.users(id) not null,
  title text,
  messages jsonb not null default '[]',
  created_at timestamptz default now(),
  updated_at timestamptz default now()
);

alter table chat_sessions enable row level security;

-- Users can only ever see their own sessions
create policy "select own sessions" on chat_sessions
  for select using (auth.uid() = user_id);

create policy "insert own sessions" on chat_sessions
  for insert with check (auth.uid() = user_id);

create policy "update own sessions" on chat_sessions
  for update using (auth.uid() = user_id);

create policy "delete own sessions" on chat_sessions
  for delete using (auth.uid() = user_id);
```

That RLS block *is* the "secure user-specific data queries" requirement â€” Postgres enforces it at the database layer, so even a compromised frontend can't read another user's rows.

3. Frontend auth (replace the demo modal in `aegis-pro.html`):

```js
import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js'
const supabase = createClient(SUPABASE_URL, SUPABASE_ANON_KEY)

// Sign up
await supabase.auth.signUp({ email, password })
// Sign in
await supabase.auth.signInWithPassword({ email, password })
// Sign out
await supabase.auth.signOut()

// Save a session (RLS auto-scopes this to the logged-in user)
await supabase.from('chat_sessions').upsert({ id: sessionId, user_id: user.id, title, messages })

// Load history
const { data } = await supabase.from('chat_sessions').select('*').order('updated_at', { ascending:false })
```

This needs a real build step (Vite/Next.js) since `import` from npm packages doesn't work in a single static HTML file â€” that's the main reason this isn't already wired into the artifact.

